<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, October 8, the 281st day of 1989. There are 84
days left in the year. Yom Kippur, the Jewish Day of Atonement,
begins at sunset.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On October 8, 1871, one of America's worst urban fires and
forest fires broke out in Chicago and Peshtigo, Wisc. The Chicago
fire claimed more than 200 lives and destroyed more than 17,000
buildings. The Wisconsin blaze claimed an estimated 1,500 lives and
scorched 1.28 million acres of timberland.
   On this date:
   In 1869, the 14th president of the United States, Franklin
Pierce, died in Concord, N.H.
   In 1918, Sergeant Alvin C. York almost single-handedly killed 25
German soldiers and captured 132 in the Argonne Forest in France.
   In 1934, Bruno Hauptmann was indicted for murder in the death of
the infant son of Charles A. Lindbergh.
   In 1939, the New York Yankees won the World Series in four games
straight, defeating the Cincinnati Reds, 7-4.
   In 1944, ``The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet'' made its debut
on CBS radio, an event that coincided with Ozzie and Harriet
Nelson's ninth wedding anniversary.
   In 1945, President Truman announced that the secret of the
atomic bomb would be shared only with Britain and Canada.
   In 1956, Don Larsen pitched the only perfect game ever in a
World Series as the New York Yankees beat the Brooklyn Dodgers, 2-0.
   In 1957, the Brooklyn Baseball Club announced it was accepting
an offer to move the Dodgers from New York to Los Angeles.
   In 1970, exiled Soviet author Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn was
awarded the Nobel Prize for literature.
   In 1981, at the White House, President Reagan greeted
predecessors Jimmy Carter, Gerald R. Ford and Richard M. Nixon
before sending them off to Egypt for the funeral of Anwar Sadat.
   In 1982, the government of Poland banned all labor
organizations, including Solidarity.
   Ten years ago: Pope John Paul II returned to Rome, having
wrapped up a nine-day journey to Ireland and the United States.
   Five years ago: In an address to the U.N. General Assembly, the
president of El Salvador, Jose Napoleon Duarte unexpectedly offered
to hold peace talks with leftist guerrillas.
   One year ago: Pope John Paul II journeyed to eastern France,
where he addressed the Council of Europe and the European Court of
Human Rights.
   Today's Birthdays: Senator Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, is 73.
Entertainment reporter Rona Barrett is 53. Actor David Carradine is
49. Reverend Jesse Jackson is 48. Comedian-actor Chevy Chase is 46.
Rock singer Johnny Ramone is 38. Actress Stephanie Zimbalist is 33.
   Thought for Today: ``I have always noticed that deeply and truly
religious persons are fond of a joke, and I am suspicious of those
who aren't.'' _ Alfred North Whitehead, English philosopher and
mathematician (1861-1947).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Sunday, October 8</NOTE>
</DOC>

